<header class="header">
  <h1>Tomato Grafting Clips vs Silicone Clips</h1>
  <p class="tagline">
    Not all grafting clips apply pressure the same way — and that difference shows up in your success rate.
  </p>
  <p class="lede">
    <strong>For most home gardeners, silicone grafting clips are easier to use and more forgiving, while rigid tomato grafting clips provide more control but require better sizing and technique.</strong>
  </p>
  <p>
    When grafting tomatoes, the clip’s job is simple: hold the scion and rootstock in perfect alignment while they heal. But how it does that — with rigid pressure or flexible support — changes how easy the process is.
  </p>
  <p>
    The difference becomes especially noticeable in home setups where seedlings are not perfectly uniform.
  </p>
</header>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Quick Answer: Which Should You Use?</h2>

  <div class="quickAnswerBox">
    <ul class="plainList">
      <li><strong>Best for beginners:</strong> silicone clips.</li>
      <li><strong>Best for precision:</strong> rigid tomato grafting clips.</li>
      <li><strong>Best overall for home use:</strong> silicone clips in the right size range.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <p>
    The easier the clip is to match and apply, the more consistent your results tend to be.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>What’s the Actual Difference?</h2>

  <p>
    The main difference is how the clip applies pressure to the graft union.
  </p>

  <div class="decisionTableWrap">
    <table class="decisionTable">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Feature</th>
          <th>Silicone Clips</th>
          <th>Rigid Grafting Clips</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Material</strong></td>
          <td>Soft, flexible silicone</td>
          <td>Hard plastic</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Pressure style</strong></td>
          <td>Gentle, adaptive</td>
          <td>Fixed, more rigid</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Fit tolerance</strong></td>
          <td>More forgiving</td>
          <td>Requires precise sizing</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
