    </table>
  </div>

  <p>
    In practice, this comes down to how closely your clip size matches your seedlings.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Why Silicone Clips Are Easier for Home Gardeners</h2>

  <p>
    Silicone clips flex around the stem instead of forcing it into a fixed shape. That means they can handle slight variation in stem size without damaging the plant or losing alignment.
  </p>

  <p>
    This matters in real home setups, where seedlings rarely grow at exactly the same rate.
  </p>

  <p>
    If your stems are slightly uneven, silicone usually still works.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Where Rigid Tomato Grafting Clips Still Shine</h2>

  <p>
    Rigid clips apply more consistent pressure when the sizing is correct. In very uniform batches, this can create a very stable graft union.
  </p>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li>more controlled alignment when sizes match closely</li>
    <li>less movement in ideal conditions</li>
    <li>useful for repeatable, consistent setups</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    The tradeoff is that they are less forgiving when things are slightly off.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Where Each One Fails</h2>

  <h3>Silicone Clips</h3>
  <ul class="plainList">
    <li>can be too loose if sizing is far off</li>
    <li>less rigid support for very thick stems</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Rigid Clips</h3>
  <ul class="plainList">
    <li>can crush delicate stems if too small</li>
    <li>can slip if too large</li>
    <li>less adaptable to variation</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Both types work well when sized correctly — but only one tolerates mistakes better.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>How Seedling Variability Changes the Decision</h2>

  <p>
    This is where most home gardeners run into trouble. Even if seeds are started at the same time, small differences in light, temperature, or watering can change stem thickness.
  </p>

  <p>
    In those conditions:
  </p>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li>silicone clips adapt better</li>
    <li>rigid clips require sorting seedlings by size</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    If you are not grading seedlings carefully, flexible clips tend to give better results.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>What Most Gardeners Get Wrong</h2>

  <h3>Focusing on Clip Type Instead of Size</h3>
  <p>
    A well-sized clip matters more than whether it is silicone or rigid.
  </p>

  <h3>Assuming Rigid Means Better</h3>
  <p>
    More pressure is not better if it damages the stem.
  </p>

  <h3>Using One Size for Everything</h3>
  <p>
    Seedlings rarely match a single size perfectly.
  </p>

  <h3>Not Accounting for Growth After Grafting</h3>
  <p>
    Clips need to accommodate slight expansion as healing begins.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Best Use by Situation</h2>

  <div class="scenarioGrid">
    <div class="scenarioCard">
      <h3>Best for Beginners</h3>
      <p>
        Silicone clips reduce the chance of damaging seedlings during setup.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="scenarioCard">
      <h3>Best for Mixed Seedling Sizes</h3>
      <p>
        Flexible clips handle variation better.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="scenarioCard">
      <h3>Best for Uniform Batches</h3>
      <p>
        Rigid clips can provide consistent pressure when everything matches closely.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="scenarioCard">
      <h3>Best for Learning Grafting</h3>
      <p>
        More forgiving tools make the process easier to repeat successfully.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>How This Fits Into a Home Grafting Setup</h2>

  <p>
    Clip choice matters, but it works alongside humidity control, timing, and cutting technique. Even the best clip cannot compensate for poor alignment or unstable conditions.
  </p>

  <p>
    For most home gardeners, reducing variables — including clip sensitivity — improves results.
  </p>

