    See <a href="/guides/2-0-to-4-5-mm-grafting-clips-for-home-gardeners/">2.0 to 4.5 mm grafting clips for home gardeners</a> and <a href="/guides/best-grafting-clips-for-cucumbers/">best grafting clips for cucumbers</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="calloutBox">
  <h2>What Most Home Gardeners Should Actually Use</h2>

  <p>
    Use silicone grafting clips in a couple of sizes that match your seedlings. They are more forgiving, easier to apply, and better suited to the variability of home-grown plants.
  </p>

  <p>
    Rigid clips can work well, but they require more precise sizing and more uniform seedlings to perform consistently.
  </p>

  <p class="muted">
    Flexibility makes grafting easier when conditions are not perfect.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Bottom Line</h2>

  <p>
    Silicone clips are generally the better choice for home gardeners because they adapt to small differences in stem size and reduce the risk of damage.
  </p>

  <p>
    Rigid tomato grafting clips can provide excellent results in controlled, uniform setups, but they are less forgiving when conditions vary.
  </p>

  <p class="muted">
    Choose flexibility unless you can control every variable.
  </p>
</section>